    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Thanks, that's a good start. I noticed you mentioned Lochner and Griswold together. Aren't some people critical of using substantive due process because they say it's basically just judges making up laws based on their own values instead of following the literal text of the Constitution? How should I address those criticisms in my lesson?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You can address this criticism by explaining that the concept of substantive due process does indeed allow judges to interpret the Constitution in a way that goes beyond its literal text. However, you can also note that the Court's use of substantive due process has been consistently applied to fundamental rights, such as freedom of speech and religious freedom, and that this approach has been remarkably successful in protecting the rights of marginalized groups. Additionally, point out that the Court has also attempted to limit the scope of substantive due process by ruling in cases such as Lawrence v. Texas, which some see as a retreat from broad, rights-based approaches.",
      "source": "target",
